Healthcare diabetic project¶

Context¶

This dataset is originally from the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases. The objective of the dataset is to diagnostically predict whether or not a patient has diabetes, based on certain diagnostic measurements included in the dataset. Several constraints were placed on the selection of these instances from a larger database. In particular, all patients here are females at least 21 years old of Pima Indian heritage.

Problem Statement¶

Build a model to accurately predict whether the patients in the dataset have diabetes or not?

Dataset Description:¶

The datasets consists of several medical predictor variables and one target variable, Outcome. Predictor variables includes the number of pregnancies the patient has had, their BMI, insulin level, age, and so on.

  1. Pregnancies: Number of times pregnant
  2. Glucose: Plasma glucose concentration a 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test
  3. BloodPressure: Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg)
  4. SkinThickness: Triceps skin fold thickness (mm)
  5. Insulin: 2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml)
  6. BMI: Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2)
  7. DiabetesPedigreeFunction: Diabetes pedigree function
  8. Age: Age (years)
  9. Outcome: Class variable (0 or 1) 268 of 768 are 1, the others are 0

from PIL import Image as PILImage
import base64, io, IPython
def image_import(image):
    image = PILImage.open(image)
    output = io.BytesIO()
    image.save(output, format='PNG')
    encoded_string = base64.b64encode(output.getvalue()).decode()
    html = '<img src="data:image/png;base64,{}"/>'.format(encoded_string)
    return IPython.display.HTML(html)

def median_replace(dataset_1):
    median_data = dataset_1.median(skipna=True)
    dataset_1_upd = dataset_1.replace(0,median_data)
    return dataset_1_upd

DiabetesPedigree function and age are not strongly correlated both have positive correlation with each other but not very strongly bounded¶

Conculsion:- We saw relationship between all the Features and some features are positively correlated and others are negatively but none of the features have very strong correlation that we can drop one column(we have less feature as well) data has little skewness due to outcome we need to remind this thing and we need 1-2 features as well becuase we are somewhere skiping the male for the data.¶

Week 2 task 3¶

Corelation matrix¶

  1. correlation matrix tells us that relationship between the different objects
  2. If two columns are heavily correlated to each other i.e they are depend upon each other
  3. In calculation or model building we can drop the one of the columns.

Week 3 task¶

Model Building and hypertunning¶

Spliting the data(Dev/train or train/test)¶

We can choose three path either we split the data in train / Test which is very old technique and in both the set ratio of diabetic or non diabetic should be same ,It is a easy technique we can use it less amount of data.¶

Second Technique : In that scenario we split the data in 3 part dev/train/test dev part all non diabetic part +(1/2)*dibetic¶

              1. Train set : All non diabetic data(500)+(.50)*diabetic(134)
              2  Dev set:(1/4)*Diabetic data
              3. Test:(1/4)*Diabetic data

Second approches requires lots of data for better result so we can use first approach¶

Third approcahes we can use k crossvalidation set(Kfold validation) which will work will in this situation¶

I will try first and third and comapre the result¶

Model Creation¶

      1. Logistic Regression
      2.Support Vector Machine (Kernal=Linear)
      3.Support Vector Machine(Krenal=rbf(non_linear))
       4.Naive Bayes
       5. K-Nearest Neighbours(KNN)
       6.Decision Tree classifier
        7.Random Forest Classifier

We can use more powerful technique which is like gradientboosting and adaboosting but data is very small so the above mention methods are sufficient¶

ROC Curve Analysis of Kfold split set¶

ROC-Receiver Operating Characterestic curve¶

It is a very useful technique when predicting the probability binary classification ,it plots false positive rate on and true positive rate on y axis

Diabetes prediction is very important issue becuase it affects the life¶

True_Positive_rate = TP/(TP+FN)

Sensitivity == True_Positive_rate

False_Positive_rate = FP/(FP+TN)

Specificity=1-False_Positive_rate

We will try to draw ROC curve on Decisiontree and KNN model

In [148]:
